ngeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Musbury, Devon, England":"Musbury, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1280–1332":"1280–1332","1270–1365":"1270–1365","1292–1327":"1292–1327","1312–Male":"1312–Deceased","1315–1373":"1315–1373","1327–1400":"1327–1400","1240–1332":"1240–1332","1244–Female":"1244–Deceased","about 1292":"about 1292","1373":"1373","1240":"1240","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1400":"1400","1312":"1312","1332":"1332","1244":"1244","1365":"1365","about 1315":"about 1315","about 1312":"about 1312","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sherford, Devon, England":"Sherford, Devon, England","Westho Parish, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Musbury, Devon, , England":"Musbury, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Musbury, Devon, England":"Musbury, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ashe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Ash   1, found mainly in Ireland.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Dufresne  , a variant of   Ash   2.","History: This is the name of a prominent NC family; John Baptist Ashe settled in NC before 1720. It is not known where he came from: his personal name suggests that he may have been of French extraction, perhaps originally named Jean-Baptiste Dufresne."],"variants":[{"name":"Ash","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>asche</i> ‘ash tree’ (Old English <i>æsc</i>), hence a topographic name for someone living by an ash tree or a habitational name from any of the many places in southern and central England named with this word (Derbyshire, Dorset, Hampshire, Herefordshire, Kent, Surrey, Shropshire, Somerset, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of German   Asch   and   Esch  , the latter ultimately also of Swiss German origin (see   Oesch  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Dufresne  , with the same meaning as 1 above."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Esse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farmstead Ese in Sogn of unexplained etymology, or Esse in Telemark, named with Old Norse <i>æsin</i> ‘hill’ + <i>-e</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’.","German: variant of   Ess  , or a topographic name from the river name Esse in Hesse."],"variants":[{"name":"Ess","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone living on or owning land that was waterlogged or partly surrounded by water, from Middle Low German <i>es</i> ‘swamp, water’.","Swiss German: from the topographic name <i>Ess</i> ‘grazing area, pasture’.","Swiss German: from a vernacular short form of the personal name   Oswald  ."]}]},{"name":"Oliver","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French name, <i>Olivier</i>, recorded as the name of one of Charlemagne's paladins (retainers), the close companion in arms of Roland in the Chanson de Roland. Whereas Roland is headstrong and rash, Oliver is thoughtful and cautious. Ostensibly this name derives from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i> ‘olive tree’ (  compare  Olive  ), but Charlemagne's other paladins all bear solidly Germanic names, so it is more probably an altered form of a Germanic name, perhaps distantly connected with Old Norse <i>Óleifr</i> ‘ancestral relic’. It has remained in more or less continuous use since the medieval period, becoming ever more popular since the 1980s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Oliver Ashe de Esse was born in 1280, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralphe de Esse, was 40 and his mother, Margaret de Ashe, was 37. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Lady Emma D'Esse Cruys. He died in 1332, in Devon, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1280–1332":"1280–1332","1270–1365":"1270–1365","1292–1327":"1292–1327","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1315–1373":"1315–1373","1327–1400":"1327–1400","1240–1332":"1240–1332","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","about 1292":"umbes 1292","1373":"1373","1240":"1240","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1280"